# iPad Prototype UX Conventions

## Back button icon

Use the **left arrow** (`ArrowLeft` from `lucide-react`) for back buttons, not the chevron.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — chevron for back
import { ChevronLeft } from "lucide-react";
<button onClick={onBack}><ChevronLeft className="w-5 h-5" /></button>

// ✅ GOOD — left arrow for back
import { ArrowLeft } from "lucide-react";
<button onClick={onBack}><ArrowLeft className="w-5 h-5 text-[#101010]" /></button>
```

Use `ChevronLeft` / `ChevronRight` only for in-context navigation (e.g. calendar month, pagination), not for “back” to a previous screen.

## No Hover Effects

This project is an iPad POS prototype. Touch devices have no hover state, so **never add hover effects** to any interactive element (buttons, inputs, textareas, tiles, etc.).

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
className="border-[#dadada] hover:border-[#101010]"
className="bg-[#f0f0f0] hover:bg-[#e0e0e0]"

// ✅ GOOD — use active: or focus: states only
className="border-[#dadada] focus:border-[#101010]"
className="bg-[#f0f0f0] active:bg-[#e0e0e0]"
```

## New Cart Items

Every `CartItem` created (whether added directly or via the add panel) must include the full set of options fields so the edit panel always has data to work with:

```ts
{
  id,
  name,
  price,
  quantity,
  description,   // from MenuItem
  modifiers,     // selected modifier ids (omit if empty)
  note: "",
  taxes: [],
  discounts: [],
  serviceCharges: [],
}
```

## Add panel ↔ Edit panel parity

When editing **Item Add Panel** (`item-add-panel.tsx`) or **Item Edit Panel** (`item-edit-panel.tsx`), apply the same styling, layout, and UX changes to the other panel so they stay in sync (e.g. header layout, modifier tile active state, section labels, typography).

## Modals and dialogs (iPad prototype)

Modals in the iPad prototype must stay **inside the iPad** and be positioned **relative to the iPad screen**, not the browser viewport.

### Rule 1: Contained within the iPad

- Modals must **not** cover the entire screen or be positioned relative to the full viewport.
- They must render inside the iPad screen container and use **absolute** positioning relative to it (so they are clipped by the iPad frame and don’t overflow).
- This is already wired up when the app is wrapped in `IPadMock`: it provides `DialogContainerProvider` with a container ref to the iPad screen. The shared `Dialog` component (in `components/ui/dialog.tsx`) uses `useDialogContainer()` and, when `contained` is true, portals into that container and switches overlay/content from `fixed` to `absolute`.
- **When adding a new modal/dialog** in the iPad prototype: use the existing `Dialog` from `@/components/ui/dialog`. Do not portal to `document.body` or use viewport-relative positioning for iPad-only flows.

### Rule 2: Position from top of iPad screen

- Modals should be positioned **68px from the top** of the iPad screen, not vertically centered over the viewport.
- Apply this by passing `className="top-[68px] translate-y-0 ..."` (and any other layout classes) to `DialogContent`. This overrides the default centered positioning and keeps the modal within the iPad.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — modal inside iPad, 68px from top of iPad screen
<DialogContent
  className="top-[68px] translate-y-0 max-w-[min(420px,calc(100vw-2rem))] ..."
>
  ...
</DialogContent>
```

## Row components (settings / detail rows)

For any **row** that shows a label on the left and control/link on the right (e.g. "Number of copies" + stepper, "Appearance" + Edit), the **left and right content must be vertically aligned at center** by default.

- Use **`items-center`** on the row container so the trailing control aligns with the center of the label (and optional subtitle).
- Use **`items-start`** only when the row has multi-line content on the left (e.g. "Categories & items" with a long list); in that case pass a prop like `largeGap` and use `items-start` when `largeGap` is true.

Do not add or reintroduce row layouts that use `items-start` for single-line rows (e.g. "Number of copies", "Appearance", "Print receipts automatically"). Single-line rows must use `items-center`.
